programme.title: Blood Origins Episode #35 - Corey Anderson "Overtime"
programme.desc: You may know Corey for who he is within the octagon. Corey "Overtime" Anderson - #5 ranked light-heavy weight in the UFC. An African American that is an unassuming character, flies below the radar, yet continues to push towards the top as a result of an unrelenting work ethic. What you may not know is that Corey is a hunter. A die-hard hunter. A hunter that takes that same ethic of outworking opponents and applies it to being the best hunter he can be. As Corey states, "label me whatever you want, but make sure that hunter is in that label".

programme.title: Blood Origins Episode #37 - Larry Weishuhn "Mr. Whitetail"
programme.desc: It's an unmistakable white beard in the outdoor industry. Match that with a cowboy hat, big-rimmed glasses, and sporting a Dallas Safari Club Pin and you will know exactly who we are talking about. A lot of people know him as Mr. Whitetail, but his real name is Larry Weishuhn. Unbeknownst to most, Larry is a wildlife biologist, a conservationist, and has cut his teeth in understanding his why behind hunting on his beloved stomping grounds of Texas. What you may or may not know is that he one of us, down to earth individual, a lover of wildlife, and a hunter.

programme.title: Blood Origins Episode #38 - Ramsey Russel "Get Ducks"
programme.desc: He goes by many names, but you may know him by what he tends to say: "It's duck season somewhere" or "Get Ducks" Some have even called him the Jim Shockey of the waterfowl world. You may also know him by his physical appearance - hands and face scarred from an unfortunate incident as a teenager where they gave him little chance to make it. You see when you look at Ramsey Russel you may be immediately taken aback by the burns, the scars, the skin grafts, but duck hunting is buried deep in his blood. Duck hunting saved him after his incident. Duck hunting gave him purpose. Duck hunting to him is not about that duck. Chasing that duck allowed him to truly hunt for experiences.

programme.title: Blood Origins Episode #39 - Paul Bride "Perspective"
programme.desc: One of the most important questions to answer to a non-hunting audience is why we hunt. Often though, it may come across as self-serving for a hunter to explain the why behind hunting. That's why the perspective of a non-hunter is absolutely imperative to listen to. That perspective is shaped by the hunters in that individual's life. Better yet, that perspective is shaped by the actions of the hunter in that persons life. Paul Bride is a world class photographer who is not a hunter. He was hired by the late Jason Hairston to come along on a sheep hunting adventure to photograph a hunt without any perspective to what hunting actually was. Listen to Paul as he describes his non-hunting perspective on hunting.

programme.title: Blood Origins #40 - Jess Byers "Failure"
programme.desc: There is a seedy underbelly within the hunting community today. An undercurrent where hunters feel the need to drag down other hunters. The reason for the hate is unknown - it could be jealousy, it could be a simple dislike of someone, or it could even be tied to an old flame. What this new culture is breeding is the perpetuation of the social media culture of perfectionism, essentially a false narrative around who hunters are supposed to be. Hunting is inherently tied within its definition to failure, and for Jessica, she understands that and is open to the world of all her failures. Failing makes you better. Failing is how one learns. Everyone fails. As a hunting community we need to embrace it. Embrace failure, don't be shy to point out the plank in our own eyes. Hunting isn't perfect, nor should the portrayal of it be.
